[[File:Anhut 3491624204 22f8d237b9 o.jpg|thumb|300px]]
'''John Nicholson Anhut''' (January 8, 1884 - May 1977) was the founder of the [[Anhut Motor Car Company]] of [[Detroit, Michigan]].

==Biography==
He married Elizabeth Bouvier Walsh. 

Anhut was elected to the Michigan Senate in 1908. After the failure of the Anhut company, he eventually moved to New York, where he gained admittance to the bar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two To Four Years Anhut's Sentence|url=http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=F00C11FC3F5B13738DDDAD0A94DD405B838DF1D3|accessdate=10 December 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 24, 1913}}</ref> 

In 1912 he was accused of attempting to bribe physicians of [[Harry K. Thaw]] while Thaw was institutionalized at the [[Matteawan State Hospital for the Criminally Insane]].<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Admits Thaw Retained Him, but in Affairs Other Than Fight for Freedom. |url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F0DE5D6163FE633A25757C2A9649C946296D6CF |quote=John N. Anhut, mentioned by Dr. John R. Russell in the Thaw bribery attempt case, spent yesterday afternoon with friends in the Union League and Lotos Clubs. He was interviewed last night in the Grand Central Station by a Times reporter. He denied emphatically that he was concerned in any attempt to procure the release of Harry K. Thaw from Matteawan. |work=[[New York Times]] |date=February 24, 1913 |accessdate=2009-12-31 }}</ref> Anhut was found guilty of bribery, and was sentenced to not less than four years in the State Prison.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two To Four Years Anhut's Sentence|url=http://query.nytimes.com/mem/archive-free/pdf?res=F00C11FC3F5B13738DDDAD0A94DD405B838DF1D3|accessdate=10 December 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 24, 1913}}</ref>

In the 1930's Anhut was active in the hotel industry, buying the Imperial and Clifford hotels in downtown Detroit, as well as being the attorney for the Detroit Hotel Association.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rudisill|first=Alvin|title=Anhuts-Father and Son|url=http://ypsigleanings.aadl.org/ypsigleanings/19528|work=Ypsilanti Gleanings|accessdate=10 December 2012}}</ref>

